        <title><m>\S 2.1</m>: Linear Combinations and Linear Systems</title>
            <page>
                <exercise workspace="2in">
                    <title>Motivation: Linear Combinations and Linear Systems</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
					<solution>
						<p>
							Last time we saw
							<ol>
								<li>
									<p>
										<m>c\vvec + d \wvec</m> can be visualized as walking along <m>\vvec</m> a total 
										of <m>c</m> times, then walking along <m>\wvec</m> a total of <m>d</m> times
										(in <m>\R^2</m>).
									</p>
								</li>
								<li>
									<p>
										In general, asking whether <m>\bvec</m> is a linear combination of other vectors
										is equivalent to asking whether a specific linear system has a solution.
									</p>
								</li>
							</ol>
						</p>
					</solution>
                    
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace="3in">
                    <title>Example: Notation</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Last time we found that <m>\bvec = \twovec{-11}{-18}</m> is a linear combination of <m>\vvec = \twovec{3}{-1}</m>
						and <m>\wvec = \twovec{4}{3}</m> because
                        </p>
                    </statement>
					<solution>
						<p>
							<me>
								\left[
								\begin{array}{rr|r}
								3 \amp 4 \amp -11 \\
								-1 \amp 3 \amp -18 \\
								\end{array}
								\right]
								\sim
								\left[
								\begin{array}{rr|r}
								1 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\
								0 \amp 1 \amp -5 \\
								\end{array}
								\right].
							</me>
							As shorthand, we will often write augmented matrices that come from linear combinations as 
							<me>
								\left[
								\begin{array}{rr|r}
								\vvec \amp \wvec \amp \bvec \\
								\end{array}
								\right].
							</me>
							
						</p>
					</solution>
                    
